            <background>
                <para>
                A few nobles - mostly those who have listened too closely to
                the tales of bards - take it upon themselves to rid the world
                of evil, to set things right, and to rescue any fair maidens
                in distress. Similar to the Landless Knight, they have no
                prospects at home, and see the wide open world as an opportunity
                to be heroes, find riches, and get the girl.
                </para>
                <para>
                Such noble adventurers seek out danger and trouble, indeed they
                often cause danger and trouble. They are far more idealistic
                than they should be, though a few years of the hard life tends
                to grind most of them down into cynicism. Those who keep their
                idealistic innocence are to be truly feared.
                </para>
